HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1210
By Wright
A RESOLUTION to recognize the 150th anniversary of the first
telephone call and the founding of AT&T.
WHEREAS, March 10, 2026, marked the 150th anniversary of the first telephone call;
that call led to the launch of the Bell Telephone Company, which eventually became American
Telephone & Telegraph and today's modern AT&T; and
WHEREAS, on March 10, 1876, Alexander Graham Bell placed the first telephone call to
his assistant, Thomas Watson, speaking the historic words, "Mr. Watson, come here. I want to
see you," thereby ushering in a new era of communication; and
WHEREAS, over the past 150 years, telecommunications innovation has transformed
how individuals live, how businesses operate, and how communities connect across the United
States and around the world; and
WHEREAS, AT&T has been a leading force in advancing connectivity and
communications throughout the United States for a century and a half; and
WHEREAS, AT&T has evolved from a landline telephone provider into a wireless,
broadband, and media company, yet its mission has remained constant: to serve Americans by
providing the connectivity necessary to stay informed, productive, and connected; and
WHEREAS, what began as a single phone call in 1876 has grown into an essential part
of everyday life, enabling individuals, families, businesses, and communities to remain
connected; and
WHEREAS, continued investment in modern communications networks and high-speed
broadband infrastructure is essential to expanding access to education, telemedicine, health
care, and economic opportunity for the residents of the State of Tennessee; now, therefore,
HJR1210
016205
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we commend AT&T on the occasion of its 150th anniversary and express
our deep appreciation for a century and a half of innovation and investment in the phone and
the future of the State of Tennessee.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
